          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How is project profitability calculated?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Project profitability is project revenue minus direct costs booked to that project, divided by project revenue. A project billing Rs 20 lakh with Rs 12 lakh of manpower, subcontract and travel cost has a margin of 40 percent. Allocated overheads such as rent and admin salaries should be shown separately, so the direct margin and the net margin are both visible."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the difference between project margin and employee utilisation?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Project margin measures revenue less direct project cost, while utilisation measures the share of available hours actually billed. A project can carry a healthy margin and still run on poor utilisation if staff sit idle between phases. Utilisation drives capacity planning and margin drives pricing, so reading both together shows whether a weak result is a rate problem or a bench problem."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How is project revenue recognised under Indian accounting standards?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Revenue on a project is recognised over time as performance obligations are satisfied under Ind AS 115, measured by costs incurred against total expected costs, and under AS 7 for construction contracts where AS applies. A project 60 percent complete on a Rs 50 lakh contract recognises Rs 30 lakh of revenue, so reported margin depends on the cost estimate staying accurate."
          }
        }
      ]
