<div class="gl-page">
  <section class="gl-hero"><div class="gl-wrap"><nav class="gl-crumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb"><a href="/">Home</a><span class="sep">&rsaquo;</span><a href="/glossary">Glossary</a><span class="sep">&rsaquo;</span><a href="/glossary/accounting">Accounting</a><span class="sep">&rsaquo;</span><span class="cur">Project-Wise Profitability Margin</span></nav><div class="gl-cat">Accounting Glossary &middot; Industry</div><h1 class="gl-h1">Project-Wise Profitability Margin</h1><div class="gl-byline"><span class="ok"><svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><path d="M9 12l2 2 4-4m6 2a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z"/></svg></span><span class="who">Reviewed by CA &amp; CS Team, Patron Accounting LLP</span><span class="sep">&middot;</span><span>Last updated 22 Jul 2026</span><span class="sep">&middot;</span><span>5 min read</span><span class="sep">&middot;</span><span class="lvl">Advanced</span></div></div></section>
  <div class="gl-tocbar"><div class="gl-wrap gl-toc"><a href="#definition" class="gl-pill is-active">Definition</a><a href="#what-is" class="gl-pill">What it is</a><a href="#how-works" class="gl-pill">How it works</a><a href="#formula" class="gl-pill">Formula</a><a href="#example" class="gl-pill">Example</a><a href="#mistakes" class="gl-pill">Mistakes</a><a href="#faq-section" class="gl-pill">FAQs</a></div></div>
  <div class="gl-body"><div class="gl-wrap"><div class="gl-grid"><div class="gl-main"><section id="definition" class="gl-sec"><div class="gl-eyebrow">Project-Wise Profitability Margin: Definition</div><div class="definition-box"><p>Project-wise profitability margin is the profit a single project earns, expressed as a percentage of its revenue, after charging all costs directly attributable to it. It is a management measure drawn from project accounting, not a statutory line. It matters because a healthy overall margin can hide loss-making projects, and only per-project analysis reveals which work actually pays.</p></div></section><section id="what-is" class="gl-sec"><h2>What Is Project-Wise Profitability Margin?</h2><p>A services or contracting business runs many projects at once, each with its own revenue, staffing and costs. Project-wise profitability margin isolates one project: it takes that project&#x27;s revenue, subtracts the labour, subcontract, materials and directly attributable overheads it consumed, and expresses the resulting profit as a margin. It converts a blended company result into a clear view of which engagements create value and which quietly drain it.</p><p>An Indian consultancy, IT services firm or construction contractor meets this measure in its MIS. A Bengaluru software services firm comparing two projects at the same ₹20,00,000 revenue may find one at a 35% margin and another, over-staffed and scope-crept, at 8%. That contrast — invisible in the company-wide profit — is what drives decisions on pricing, staffing and which clients to take on. It relies on clean allocation of cost and properly recognised revenue, including unbilled WIP.</p><div class="key-terms"><p class="key-terms__title">Key terms</p><ul><li><a href="/glossary/accounting/gstr-2b-input-tax-credit-matching">GSTR-2B Input Tax Credit Matching</a> — Input-credit reconciliation feeding accurate project costs.</li><li><a href="/glossary/accounting/section-194q-tds-on-goods">Section 194Q TDS on Goods</a> — TDS on high-value goods purchases.</li><li><a href="/glossary/accounting/landing-cost-adjustment">Landing Cost Adjustment</a> — Loading freight and duty into the true cost of goods.</li></ul></div></section><section id="how-works" class="gl-sec"><h2>How Project-Wise Profitability Margin Is Used in Financial Analysis</h2><p>Managers and owners read project margins to steer the business:</p><ol class="step-cards"><li class="step-card"><span class="step-num">1</span><strong>Capture project revenue</strong><p>Billed and unbilled revenue for the project is gathered from the billing and WIP records — the top line.</p></li><li class="step-card"><span class="step-num">2</span><strong>Attribute direct costs</strong><p>Labour hours, subcontractors, materials and directly attributable overheads are charged to the project.</p></li><li class="step-card"><span class="step-num">3</span><strong>Compute the margin</strong><p>Project profit divided by project revenue gives the profitability margin as a percentage.</p></li><li class="step-card"><span class="step-num">4</span><strong>Compare across projects</strong><p>Margins are ranked so strong and weak engagements stand out against the blended average.</p></li><li class="step-card"><span class="step-num">5</span><strong>Act on the read</strong><p>Owners reprice, restaff or exit low-margin work, and lenders and investors read consistency of project margins as a quality signal.</p></li></ol></section><section id="sector" class="gl-sec"><h2>Where Project-Wise Profitability Margin Applies — Professional Services Firms</h2><p>Per-project margin matters wherever revenue and cost gather by engagement:</p><ul class="gloss-bullets"><li><strong>IT and software services</strong> — Firms running many client projects need per-project margins to price and staff.</li><li><strong>Consulting and advisory</strong> — Engagement-level profitability guides which work to pursue.</li><li><strong>Construction and EPC</strong> — Contract margins are tracked project by project against budget.</li><li><strong>Agencies and studios</strong> — Campaign and retainer profitability is compared across clients.</li><li><strong>MIS and board reporting</strong> — Any project business reporting to owners uses project margin as a core metric.</li></ul><p class="inline-links">See also: <a href="/accounting-services-for-the-service-sector-industry">Service Sector Accounting (Project Billing)</a> <a href="/mis-reporting-services">MIS Reporting Services</a></p></section><section id="formula" class="gl-sec"><h2>How to Calculate Project-Wise Profitability Margin</h2><div class="formula-box"><code>Project profitability margin % = (Project revenue − Directly attributable project costs) ÷ Project revenue × 100</code></div><div class="gloss-table-wrap"><table class="gloss-table"><thead><tr><th>Input</th><th>Where it comes from</th><th>Sample value (INR)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Project revenue</td><td>Billed + unbilled revenue for the project</td><td>20,00,000</td></tr><tr><td>Direct project costs</td><td>Labour, subcontract, materials, direct overheads</td><td>13,00,000</td></tr><tr><td>Project profit</td><td>Revenue minus direct costs</td><td>7,00,000</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p class="worked-result">Margin = (20,00,000 − 13,00,000) ÷ 20,00,000 × 100 = 35% — healthy, and a clear benchmark against a weaker project on the same revenue.</p></section><section id="example" class="gl-sec"><h2>Project-Wise Profitability Margin: A Practical Example</h2><div class="gloss-table-wrap"><table class="gloss-table"><thead><tr><th>Particulars</th><th>Amount (INR)</th><th>Treatment</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Project A revenue</td><td>20,00,000</td><td>Billed + unbilled</td></tr><tr><td>Project A direct costs</td><td>13,00,000</td><td>Labour, subcontract, overheads</td></tr><tr><td>Project A margin</td><td>35%</td><td>7,00,000 ÷ 20,00,000</td></tr><tr><td>Project B revenue</td><td>20,00,000</td><td>Same top line</td></tr><tr><td>Project B margin</td><td>8%</td><td>Over-staffed, scope crept</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>A Bengaluru software services firm runs two projects each at ₹20,00,000 revenue. Project A consumes ₹13,00,000 of direct cost for a 35% margin; Project B, over-staffed and hit by scope creep, returns just 8%. The company-wide P&amp;L, blending the two, would show a comfortable-looking average and hide Project B&#x27;s problem. The per-project margin exposes it, prompting the firm to renegotiate scope and restaff before the next engagement is priced the same way.</p></section><div class="gl-callout gl-callout--error"><span class="gl-callout__ic">!</span><div><div class="gl-callout__label">Common error</div><p>Not attributing labour by project: Spreading staff cost evenly hides which project is over-staffed → charge actual hours to each project.</p></div></div><section id="mistakes" class="gl-sec"><h2>Common Mistakes With Project-Wise Profitability Margin</h2><p>Project margins mislead when costs and revenue are captured loosely:</p><ul class="gloss-bullets"><li><strong>Not attributing labour by project</strong> — Spreading staff cost evenly hides which project is over-staffed → charge actual hours to each project.</li><li><strong>Ignoring unbilled revenue</strong> — Measuring only invoiced revenue distorts in-progress projects → include earned unbilled WIP.</li><li><strong>Omitting directly attributable overheads</strong> — Leaving out project-specific overheads overstates margin → attribute costs that clearly belong to the project.</li><li><strong>Reading only the company average</strong> — A healthy blended margin masks loss-making work → analyse margin project by project.</li></ul></section><section id="related" class="gl-sec"><h2>Related Accounting Terms</h2><p>Terms read alongside project margins:</p><ul class="related-terms"><li><a href="/glossary/accounting/gstr-2b-input-tax-credit-matching">GSTR-2B Input Tax Credit Matching</a> — Input-credit reconciliation feeding project cost.</li><li><a href="/glossary/accounting/section-194q-tds-on-goods">Section 194Q TDS on Goods</a> — TDS on high-value goods purchases.</li><li><a href="/glossary/accounting/landing-cost-adjustment">Landing Cost Adjustment</a> — Loading freight and duty into true cost.</li><li><a href="/glossary/accounting">Accounting Terms Glossary</a> — Browse every accounting term in one place.</li></ul></section><div class="gl-callout gl-callout--summary"><span class="gl-callout__ic">&#10003;</span><div><div class="gl-callout__label">Quick summary</div><p>Project-wise profitability margin is the profit a single project earns, expressed as a percentage of its revenue, after charging all costs directly attributable to it. It is a management measure drawn from project accounting, not a statutory line. It matters because a healthy overall margin can hide loss-making projects, and only per-project analysis reveals which work actually pays.</p></div></div><section class="gl-cta"><div class="gl-cta__t"><h3>Need help with Project-Wise Profitability Margin?</h3><p>Project-Wise Profitability Margin sits inside your day-to-day books. Patron's CA-led team keeps them accurate, compliant and audit-ready.</p></div><div class="gl-cta__btns"><a class="gl-cta__primary" href="/accounting-services">Accounting &amp; Bookkeeping Services in India &rarr;</a><a class="gl-cta__phone" href="tel:+919459456700">Book a consultation: +91 94594 56700</a></div></section></div><aside class="gl-aside"><div class="gl-card gl-card--service"><div class="gl-card__eyebrow">Related service</div><div class="gl-card__name">Accounting &amp; Bookkeeping Services in India</div><p>CA-led bookkeeping, compliance and reporting for Indian businesses.</p><a class="gl-card__cta" href="/accounting-services">Explore the service &rarr;</a></div><div class="gl-card"><div class="gl-card__eyebrow">Related terms</div><ul><li><a href="/glossary/accounting">Accounting Terms Glossary<span class="arw">&rarr;</span></a></li></ul></div></aside></div></div></div>
  <section id="faq-section" class="gl-faq-section"><div class="faq-expanded"><aside class="faq-expanded__aside"><h2 class="faq-expanded__title">Project-Wise Profitability Margin FAQs</h2><p class="faq-expanded__lead">Common questions about Project-Wise Profitability Margin for Indian businesses.</p><a class="faq-expanded__cta" href="/contact-us">Still have a question? Talk to a CA &rarr;</a><form class="faq-enquiry" action="https://www.patronaccounting.com/enquiry" method="post" novalidate><h3 class="faq-enquiry__title">Talk to a CA about your books</h3><p class="faq-enquiry__sub">Share your accounting software and we'll scope the work.</p><p class="faq-enquiry__context">Enquiring about: <strong>Project-Wise Profitability Margin</strong></p><input class="faq-enquiry__input" type="text" name="name" placeholder="Your name" required><input class="faq-enquiry__input" type="email" name="email" placeholder="Email" required><div class="faq-enquiry__phone"><span class="faq-enquiry__cc">+91</span><input class="faq-enquiry__input faq-enquiry__input--phone" type="tel" name="phone" placeholder="Mobile" required></div><button class="faq-enquiry__btn" type="submit">Get a Callback</button><p class="faq-enquiry__msg" role="status" aria-live="polite"></p><div class="faq-enquiry__badges"><span class="faq-enquiry__badge"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><path d="M9 12l2 2 4-4m6 2a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z"/></svg>CA-led team</span></div></form></aside><div class="faq-expanded__list"><div class="faq-expanded__item"><h3 class="faq-expanded__q" aria-expanded="true" aria-controls="faq-a1">How is project profitability calculated?</h3><div class="faq-expanded__a" id="faq-a1"><p>Project profitability is project revenue minus direct costs booked to that project, divided by project revenue. A project billing Rs 20 lakh with Rs 12 lakh of manpower, subcontract and travel cost has a margin of 40 percent. Allocated overheads such as rent and admin salaries should be shown separately, so the direct margin and the net margin are both visible.</p></div></div><div class="faq-expanded__item"><h3 class="faq-expanded__q" aria-expanded="true" aria-controls="faq-a2">What is the difference between project margin and employee utilisation?</h3><div class="faq-expanded__a" id="faq-a2"><p>Project margin measures revenue less direct project cost, while utilisation measures the share of available hours actually billed. A project can carry a healthy margin and still run on poor utilisation if staff sit idle between phases. Utilisation drives capacity planning and margin drives pricing, so reading both together shows whether a weak result is a rate problem or a bench problem.</p></div></div><div class="faq-expanded__item"><h3 class="faq-expanded__q" aria-expanded="true" aria-controls="faq-a3">How is project revenue recognised under Indian accounting standards?</h3><div class="faq-expanded__a" id="faq-a3"><p>Revenue on a project is recognised over time as performance obligations are satisfied under Ind AS 115, measured by costs incurred against total expected costs, and under AS 7 for construction contracts where AS applies. A project 60 percent complete on a Rs 50 lakh contract recognises Rs 30 lakh of revenue, so reported margin depends on the cost estimate staying accurate.</p></div></div></div></div></section>
